Arik Air yesterday said it has received two aircraft which went for c-check while also assuring of hitch-free operations ahead of the yuletide festivals. The two aircraft include a Q-400 and a Boeing 737-800 which check was conducted by Lufthansa Technik AG in Malta. The arrival of the aircraft, according to the airline was part of the drive of the current management led by the Assets Management Corporation of Nigeria (AMCON) will improve the number of serviceable aircraft in the airline’s fleet. In a statement, the airline said the effort is yielding results with two more aircraft expected to return from C-checks in the next few weeks – one at the end of the year, and the other in January. The Chief Executive Officer of Arik, Capt. Roy Ilegbodu, said since the current management took over the airline operation, its Earnings Before Interest, Taxes, Depreciation and Amortization (EBITDA) have been positive. He said: “We are pleased to announce the return of some of our airplanes, following positive resolution of our outstanding debts with African Export Import Bank (AFREXIM) and strong support from Lufthansa Technik AG.’’ Airlines closure is choking passengers Why Nigerian airlines die Investors deserve respects from public servants, officials – Air Peace CEO